{"title_page": "William Fiero Russell", "text_new": "{{Infobox Congressman \n | honorific_prefix = \n | name        = William Fiero Russell\n | honorific_suffix = \n | image       = File:William Fiero Russell.jpg\n | alt         = \n | state       =  [[New York (state)|New York]]\n | district    =  [[New York's 11th congressional district|11th]]\n | term_start  =  March 4, 1857\n | term_end    =  March 3, 1859\n | predecessor =  [[Rufus H. King]]\n | successor   =  [[William S. Kenyon (New York politician)|William S. Kenyon]]\n | prior_term  =\n| <!--Current office-->\n| state_assembly2= New York\n| district2      = Ulster\n| term_start2    = 1851\n| term_end2      = 1851\n| predecessor2   = [[Milton Sheldon]]\n| successor2     = [[Jacob S. Freer]]\n| <!--Personal data-->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1812|01|14}}\n| birth_place   = [[Saugerties, New York|Saugerties]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1896|04|26|1812|01|14}}\n| death_place   = Saugerties, New York, U.S.\n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| residence     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| profession    = Businessman, banker\n| religion      = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n'''William Fiero Russell''' (January 14, 1812 \u2013 April 29, 1896) was an American banker and [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from New York.\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Saugerties (town), New York|Saugerties, New York]] on January 14, 1812 to [[Jeremiah Russell]].  He completed preparatory studies, and then became active in several businesses, often ventures in which his father also had an interest.\n\nHe was the founder and president of the Saugerties Bank.  He served as postmaster of Saugerties from October 19, 1836, to January 25, 1841.  Russell was a member of the [[New York State Assembly]] (Ulster Co., 1st D.) in [[74th New York State Legislature|1851]].\n\nRussell was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[35th United States Congress]], holding office from March 4, 1857, to March 3, 1859.\n\nHe was appointed as Naval Officer of the Port of New York City in 1859, and he served until 1861.  (U.S. ports were run by three political appointees\u2014the collector, naval officer (or navy agent) and surveyor.  These individuals were responsible for assessing customs duties on incoming cargo and ensuring payment to the Department of the Treasury.  Because they were paid a percentage of duties collected as well as a portion of the fines levied for attempting to evade customs, and because employees of the customs houses were political party loyalists who were expected to contribute to their party, the collector, naval officer and surveyor positions were sought after political plums.)\n\nAfter leaving the Naval Officer's post Russell returned to his banking business.\n\nHe died in [[Saugerties (town), New York|Saugerties, New York]] on April 29, 1896. He was interred in Mountain View Cemetery.\n\n==Sources==\n{{CongBio|R000542}}\n*{{Findagrave|6944323}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-hs}}\n{{succession box | title = [[New York State Assembly]] <br>Ulster County, 1st District | before = [[Milton Sheldon]] | years = 1851 | after = [[Jacob S. Freer]]}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York |\n  district=11 |\n  before=[[Rufus H. King]] |\n  after=[[William S. Kenyon (New York politician)|William S. Kenyon]] |\n  years=1857\u20131859\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Bioguide}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russell, William Fiero}}\n[[Category:1812 births]]\n[[Category:1896 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:People from Saugerties, New York]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Congressman \n | honorific_prefix = \n | name        = William Fiero Russell\n | honorific_suffix = \n | image       = File:William Fiero Russell.jpg\n | alt         = \n | state       =  [[New York (state)|New York]]\n | district    =  [[New York's 11th congressional district|11th]]\n | term_start  =  March 4, 1857\n | term_end    =  March 3, 1859\n | predecessor =  [[Rufus H. King]]\n | successor   =  [[William S. Kenyon (New York politician)|William S. Kenyon]]\n | prior_term  =\n| <!--Current office-->\n| state_assembly2= New York\n| district2      = Ulster's 1st\n| term_start2    = 1851\n| term_end2      = 1851\n| predecessor2   = [[Milton Sheldon]]\n| successor2     = [[Jacob S. Freer]]\n| <!--Personal data-->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1812|01|14}}\n| birth_place   = [[Saugerties, New York|Saugerties]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1896|04|26|1812|01|14}}\n| death_place   = Saugerties, New York, U.S.\n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| residence     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| profession    = Businessman, banker\n| religion      = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n'''William Fiero Russell''' (January 14, 1812 \u2013 April 29, 1896) was an American banker and [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from New York.\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Saugerties (town), New York|Saugerties, New York]] on January 14, 1812 to [[Jeremiah Russell]].  He completed preparatory studies, and then became active in several businesses, often ventures in which his father also had an interest.\n\nHe was the founder and president of the Saugerties Bank.  He served as postmaster of Saugerties from October 19, 1836, to January 25, 1841.  Russell was a member of the [[New York State Assembly]] (Ulster Co., 1st D.) in [[74th New York State Legislature|1851]].\n\nRussell was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[35th United States Congress]], holding office from March 4, 1857, to March 3, 1859.\n\nHe was appointed as Naval Officer of the Port of New York City in 1859, and he served until 1861.  (U.S. ports were run by three political appointees\u2014the collector, naval officer (or navy agent) and surveyor.  These individuals were responsible for assessing customs duties on incoming cargo and ensuring payment to the Department of the Treasury.  Because they were paid a percentage of duties collected as well as a portion of the fines levied for attempting to evade customs, and because employees of the customs houses were political party loyalists who were expected to contribute to their party, the collector, naval officer and surveyor positions were sought after political plums.)\n\nAfter leaving the Naval Officer's post Russell returned to his banking business.\n\nHe died in [[Saugerties (town), New York|Saugerties, New York]] on April 29, 1896. He was interred in Mountain View Cemetery.\n\n==Sources==\n{{CongBio|R000542}}\n*{{Findagrave|6944323}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-hs}}\n{{succession box | title = [[New York State Assembly]] <br>Ulster County, 1st District | before = [[Milton Sheldon]] | years = 1851 | after = [[Jacob S. Freer]]}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York |\n  district=11 |\n  before=[[Rufus H. King]] |\n  after=[[William S. Kenyon (New York politician)|William S. Kenyon]] |\n  years=1857\u20131859\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Bioguide}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russell, William Fiero}}\n[[Category:1812 births]]\n[[Category:1896 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:People from Saugerties, New York]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States H