{"title_page": "Joey Lawrence", "text_new": "{{about|the American actor|other people named Joey Lawrence|Joey Lawrence (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Joey Lawrence\n| image        = Melissa Joan Hart and Joey Lawrence March of Dimes 414 (5673496652) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = Lawrence in 2017\n| birth_name   = Joseph Lawrence Mignogna Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=y|1976|04|20}} \n| birth_place  = [[Abington Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Abington, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| other_names  = Joe Lawrence, Joseph Lawrence\n| education    =  [[Abington Friends School]] <small>(1994)</small><br/> [[University of Southern California]]\n| occupation   = [[Actor]], [[singer-songwriter]], [[record producer]], [[game show host]]\n| years_active = 1982\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Michelle Vella<br/>|2002|2005|end=div}}<br/>{{marriage|Chandie Yawn-Nelson<br/>|2005|}}\n| children     = 2\n| family       = [[Matthew Lawrence]] <small>(brother)</small><br/>[[Andrew Lawrence (actor)|Andrew Lawrence]] <small>(brother)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Lawrence Mignogna Jr.''' (born April 20, 1976)<ref name=filmref /> is an American actor, musician, and game show host. He got his start as a child star in the early 1980s and is best known for his role as Joey Russo in ''[[Blossom (TV series)|Blossom]]''. Lawrence also starred in the series ''[[Brotherly Love (1995 TV series)|Brotherly Love]]'' with his real-life brothers [[Matthew Lawrence|Matthew]] and [[Andrew Lawrence (actor)|Andrew]].\n\n==Early life==\nLawrence was born in [[Abington Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Abington, Pennsylvania]],<ref name=filmref /> and raised in [[Philadelphia]], the son of Donna, a personnel manager and former elementary school teacher<ref>{{cite news |url=https://people.com/archive/a-method-to-his-doofus-vol-39-no-10/|title=A Method to His Doofus |first=Tom|last=Gliatto|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=March 15, 1993|accessdate=September 23, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020064723/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20109971,00.html|archivedate=October 20, 2012|df=}}</ref> and Joseph Lawrence Mignogna, an insurance broker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/49/Joey-Lawrence.html |title=Joey Lawrence Biography (1976-)| publisher= FilmReference.com|accessdate= March 20, 2017|archivedate= July 31, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180731093705/http://www.filmreference.com/film/49/Joey-Lawrence.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popeater.com/2010/07/26/joey-lawrence-sitcom-melissa-and-joey|title=Grown Up Joey Lawrence Kept the 'Y' - Here's Why |publisher=PopEater.com|accessdate=2011-11-25}}</ref> He is of Italian, Scottish and English descent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.popeater.com/2010/07/26/joey-lawrence-sitcom-melissa-and-joey|title=Grown Up Joey Lawrence Kept the 'Y' \u2014 Here's Why|first=Nicki|last=Gostin|publisher=PopEater.com |date=July 26, 2010 |accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref> His family's surname was changed to \"Lawrence\" during his childhood. He has two younger brothers, [[Matthew Lawrence|Matt]] and [[Andrew Lawrence (actor)|Andy]], who are also actors.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,306323,00.html |title=Stonecoldfox |first=Vicki Jo|last=Radovsky |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |date=April 23, 1993 |accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Abington Friends School]] in [[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania]], in 1994, and later attended the [[University of Southern California]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=1994-06-27|title=Class of '94|journal=People|volume=41|issue=24|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20103320,00.html|issn=0093-7673}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Acting===\nLawrence's first acting role was in a [[Cracker Jack]] commercial. At the age of five, he appeared on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'', where he performed the song \"[[Give My Regards to Broadway]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/joey-lawrence/bio/157668|title=Joey Lawrence|publisher=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]]|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter appearing in guest spots on ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'' and ''[[Silver Spoons]]'', Lawrence won the role of Joey Donovan on the hit [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[Gimme a Break!]]'' in 1983. He continued in that role until the series ended in 1987. 1985 marked Lawrence's theatrical debut with the release of ''[[Summer Rental]]''. Lawrence provided the voice of Oliver, the protagonist in the 1988 [[Disney]] film ''[[Oliver & Company]]''. From 1991\u201395, Lawrence co-starred in the hit TV series ''[[Blossom (TV series)|Blossom]]'', playing Joey Russo.\n\nLawrence has also starred in the series ''[[Brotherly Love (1995 TV series)|Brotherly Love]]'' (which featured his real life brothers, Matthew and Andrew Lawrence) and ''[[Run of the House]]'' and has guest starred on such programs as  ''[[American Dreams]]'' and ''[[CSI: NY]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,353091,00.html|title='Whoa' Be Gone|first=Dan|last=Snierson|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 16, 2002|accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref> One of Lawrence's film credits is ''[[Urban Legends: Final Cut]]'' (2000).\n\n[[File:Melissa & Joey cast and crew at Paley Center.jpg|thumb|left|Lawrence with the cast of ''[[Melissa & Joey]]'']]\nIn 2006, Lawrence appeared on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. Paired with professional dancer [[Edyta \u015aliwi\u0144ska]], he placed third in the competition.\n\nIn May 2007, he starred in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] hit ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'' as Billy Flynn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/107810-Joey-Lawrence-Joins-Broadways-Chicago-May-4|title=Joey Lawrence Joins Broadway's Chicago May 4|last=Gans|first=Andrew|date=2007-05-04|publisher=playbill.com|accessdate=June 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016051701/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/107810-Joey-Lawrence-Joins-Broadways-Chicago-May-4|archivedate=October 16, 2012}}</ref> He next hosted a dance competition show on [[The Learning Channel]], ''Master of Dance'', which premiered June 9, 2008.<ref>[http://tlc.discovery.com/spotlight/master-of-dance.html Master of Dance] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530000844/http://tlc.discovery.com/spotlight/master-of-dance.html |date=2008-05-30 }}, tlc.discovery.com; accessed March 20, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lawrence starred in the television movie ''[[My Fake Fianc\u00e9]]'' with [[Melissa Joan Hart]], which premiered on [[ABC Family]] to 3.6 million viewers, becoming the most-watched television movie of the ratings season, sweeping top rank in its time-period in key demos. In August 2010, Lawrence returned to television in the ABC Family sitcom ''[[Melissa & Joey]]'', again opposite Hart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7018277538?Melissa%20Joan%20Hart,%20Nikki%20Blonsky%20Among%20Stars%20To%20Appear%20In%20New%20ABC%20Family%20Shows#ixzz0qcjeaVpE|title=Melissa Joan Hart, Nikki Blonsky Among Stars To Appear In New ABC Family Shows|last=Bockelman|first=Andy|date=2010-04-01|publisher=allheadlinenews.com|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Hart plays a woman who hires Lawrence as a nanny to help care for her incarcerated sister's kids. Lawrence's character is a former figure in the financial industry whose company came under investigation for wrongdoing and caused his professional life to be put on hold. Lawrence's brothers have guest starred on the show. [[Matthew Lawrence]] played Tony Longo in season 1 episode 25 and [[Andrew Lawrence (actor)|Andrew Lawrence]] appeared in season 1 episode 26 as Ryder Scanlon's teacher, Evan McKay. The series was renewed for its fourth season and ended in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/hart-lawrence-land-tv-sitcom_1130515|title=Hart & Lawrence Land New Sitcom|accessdate=2010-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he was contracted to be a [[Chippendales]] dancer for a special engagement in June at the [[Rio All Suite Hotel and Casino]] in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/2012/05/16/joey-lawrence-stripper-chippendales|title=Joey Lawrence&nbsp;\u2013 Whoa, I'm a Stripper!|date=May 16, 2012|work=[[TMZ (website)|TMZ]]|accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref> On March 19, 2013, Lawrence began appearing in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] reality show ''[[Splash (TV series)|Splash]]'', which he co-hosts alongside [[Charissa Thompson]].\n\n===Music career===\nLawrence has said that music was always his passion, and at the height of his success began a recording career. Lawrence was 16 when his debut album ''[[Joey Lawrence (album)|Joey Lawrence]]'' was released in February 1993. Produced by [[Steve Barri]], [[Tony Peluso]], Terry Lupton and Ian Prince. Lawrence co-wrote some material, including the international hit single \"[[Nothin' My Love Can't Fix]]\" (#6 [[Billboard Hot 100 Airplay]], #10 Billboard Top 40 Mainstream, #19 [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], #13 United Kingdom, #68 Australia).<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r168277|pure_url=yes}}|title=Joey Lawrence: Billboard chart history|publisher=allmusic.com|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}</ref> The song was used as the end-title theme from the movie ''[[Cop and a Half]]''; its music video received heavy airplay on [[MTV]] and [[MuchMusic]], and Lawrence was invited to perform live on MTV's Spring Break, ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]'', and the UK's ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' in 1993.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nIn June 2011, he released a single, \"Rolled\", which was available as a free download for one week on ABC Family's website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2011/06/24/abc-familys-hit-comedy-melissa-and-joey-returns-with-all-new-episodes-premiering-wednesday-june-29-at-800-et-pt-736312/20110624abcfamily01/|title=ABC Family's Hit Comedy \"Melissa & Joey\" Returns With All-New Episodes, Premiering Wednesday, June 29 at 8:00 ET/PT|date=2011-06-24|publisher=thefutoncritic.com|accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref> In July, Joey released a second single, \"Give It To Ya (Acoustic)\" via [[Pledge Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/artists/joeylawrence/widgets/1836|title=Give it to ya|publisher=PledgeMusic|accessdate=2011-11-25}}</ref> In 2017 Joey started a band with Matt and Andy called Still 3. They released their debut single \"Lose Myself\".<ref>[http://people.com/music/joey-lawrence-brothers-new-song-still-free/ Whoa! Hear Joey Lawrence's New Song with Brothers Matthew and Andy <!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLawrence married Michelle Vella in 2002; the couple divorced in 2005. He met his second wife, Chandie Yawn-Nelson, earlier while on vacation in [[Disney World]] when the two were teenagers; they wed there in July 2005.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rizzo|first=Monica|date=2006-11-13|title=Whoa, It's Joey!|journal=People|volume=66|issue=20|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20059931,00.html|issn=0093-7673}}</ref> The couple has two children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20320041,00.html|title=Joey Lawrence, Wife Expecting Second Daughter|last=Michaud|first=Sarah|date=2009-11-13|publisher=people.com|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20348831,00.html|title=Joey Lawrence Welcomes Second Daughter|last=Michaud|first=Sarah|date=2010-03-04|publisher=people.com|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nReports surfaced in March 2018 that Lawrence and Yawn-Nelson had filed for bankruptcy in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/joey-lawrence-files-bankruptcy-accumulating-213808321.html|title=Joey Lawrence files for bankruptcy after accumulating over $355K in liabilities|author=Dave Quinn|publisher=People|date=2018-03-09|accessdate=2018-03-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theblast.com/joey-lawrence-bankruptcy/|title=Joey Lawrence Filed for Bankruptcy After Things Got So Bad, He Had to Sell His Clothes|author=Ryan Naumann|publisher=Blast|date=2018-03-09|accessdate=2018-03-10}}</ref>  On 6 April 2018, the [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 7 bankruptcy case]] was reportedly settled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theblast.com/joey-lawrence-bankruptcy-case-settled/|title=Joey Lawrence\u2019s Bankruptcy Case Comes to a Close, Several Creditors Get the Shaft|author=Ryan Naumann and Daniel Goldblatt|publisher=Blast|date=2018-04-09|accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/joey-lawrences-bankruptcy-case-settled/|title=Joey Lawrence\u2019s Bankruptcy Case Settled, IRS Won\u2019t Receive Full Payment|author=Sarah Hearon|publisher=Us Weekly|date=2018-04-09|accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Summer Rental]]''\n|Bobby Chester\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1988\n|''[[Pulse (1988 film)|Pulse]]''\n|David Rockland\n|\n|-\n|''[[Oliver & Company]]''\n|Oliver (voice)\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Chains of Gold]]''\n|Tommy\n|\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Radioland Murders]]''\n|Frankie Marshall\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''{{sortname|A|Goofy Movie}}''\n|Chad (voice)\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Tequila Body Shots]]''\n|Johnny Orpheus\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2000\n|''[[Urban Legends: Final Cut]]''\n|Graham Manning\n|\n|-\n|''[[Desperate But Not Serious]]''\n|Darby\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2001\n|''[[Do You Wanna Know a Secret?]]''\n|Hank Ford\n|\n|-\n|''{{sortname|A|Christmas Adventure ...From